  I want you to build a custom Claude Code status line — a persistent bar at the bottom of the
   interface that gives me a real-time dashboard of my session. The status line is a script
  that Claude Code runs after each assistant message. It receives a JSON object on stdin and
  prints whatever you want displayed.

  What I Want

  Build a four-row status line that covers limits, token activity, session context, and
  location at a glance. Use color coding to make high values stand out: green for healthy,
  yellow for moderate, red for high. Here are the four rows:

  Row 1 — Gauges: Three bracketed gauges showing context window usage, 5-hour rate limit, and
  7-day rate limit. Each shows a label and a percentage. The rate limit gauges should also
  show when the window resets (e.g., "4:32p" if it resets today, "Fri 4:32p" if it's further
  out).

  Row 2 — Tokens: Three bracketed segments showing cumulative input tokens, cumulative output
  tokens, and cache activity (tokens written to cache this call / tokens read from cache this
  call). Add a small delta indicator next to each showing the increment from the most recent
  API call.

  Row 3 — Session: Current model name, effort level (read from a custom effortLevel key in the
   project or user settings.json file), and elapsed session duration formatted compactly
  (e.g., 45s, 12m, 1h23m).

  Row 4 — Location: Current working directory (with ~ for the home path), git branch, and
  Salesforce default org username (read from .sfdx/sfdx-config.json in the working directory
  if present).

  Data Sources (from the Official Anthropic Status Line Docs)

  The JSON object piped to your script contains these relevant fields:

  - model.display_name — Human-readable model name (e.g., "Sonnet", "Opus")
  - workspace.current_dir — Full path of the current working directory (preferred over cwd for
   consistency)
  - context_window.used_percentage — Pre-calculated percentage of the context window in use;
  may be null before the first API call, so default to 0
  - context_window.total_input_tokens — Cumulative input tokens sent across the entire session
  - context_window.total_output_tokens — Cumulative output tokens generated across the entire
  session
  - context_window.current_usage.input_tokens — Input tokens in the most recent API call
  - context_window.current_usage.output_tokens — Output tokens generated in the most recent
  API call
  - context_window.current_usage.cache_creation_input_tokens — Tokens written to cache in the
  most recent call
  - context_window.current_usage.cache_read_input_tokens — Tokens read from cache in the most
  recent call
  - rate_limits.five_hour.used_percentage — Percent of the 5-hour rolling rate limit consumed
  (Claude.ai Pro/Max only; absent for API users)
  - rate_limits.five_hour.resets_at — Unix epoch seconds when the 5-hour window resets
  - rate_limits.seven_day.used_percentage — Percent of the 7-day rate limit consumed
  - rate_limits.seven_day.resets_at — Unix epoch seconds when the 7-day window resets
  - cost.total_duration_ms — Total elapsed milliseconds since the session started

  A few fields to handle carefully: context_window.current_usage is null before the first API
  call. rate_limits is absent entirely for API-key users (not Claude.ai subscribers). Always
  provide fallbacks for null and missing fields.

  The effortLevel value in Row 3 is NOT from Claude Code's JSON — read it yourself from the
  first effortLevel key found in .claude/settings.local.json, then .claude/settings.json in
  the working directory, then ~/.claude/settings.json. If none found, show "?".

  For the git branch in Row 4, read it directly from the .git/HEAD file by walking up the
  directory tree — no need to shell out to git.

  For the Salesforce org in Row 4, read the defaultusername field from .sfdx/sfdx-config.json
  in the working directory. Show only the part before the @ symbol to keep it compact.

